>>34871918
And following on from yet another Anon, sometimes you have the beginning, or just the characters. Sometimes you get the middle, and have to piece together what led to it, and what happens after.
I'm of the opinion a writer that knows his characters has half the work done. For your characters, what led them to the situation as is in your story? What might change their opinions? What are they avoiding, or dislike? How has the situation put them off balance, and what do they do to get back to normalcy?

Don't be afraid to sketch out a scene, then flesh it out later. Listen to your characters. It sounds autistic, and strangely not because you're focusing on one element at a time.
Try writing some dialogue, or just paint a picture with words of the room. Latch onto anything you can.
The rest will flow, if you let it.
